{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Statutory Regulations",
      "simpleDefinition": "Legally binding laws passed by Parliament that must be followed to avoid criminal prosecution.",
      "anchor": "The Law of the Land.",
      "misconception": "Believing that these are just industry suggestions rather than mandatory legal requirements."
    },
    {
      "term": "Non-statutory Regulations",
      "simpleDefinition": "Guidance documents and codes of practice that describe the best way to work safely and meet legal standards.",
      "anchor": "The Industry's Rulebook.",
      "misconception": "Thinking that because they aren't 'laws' themselves, they can be ignored without professional or legal consequence."
    },
    {
      "term": "HASAWA (Health and Safety at Work Act)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The main piece of UK legislation that sets out the general duties of employers and employees for workplace safety.",
      "anchor": "The Umbrella Act.",
      "misconception": "Thinking it only applies to the boss; it actually places legal duties on every worker."
    },
    {
      "term": "EAWR (Electricity at Work Regulations)",
      "simpleDefinition": "Statutory laws specifically designed to ensure electrical systems are safe to prevent death or injury.",
      "anchor": "The Electrician's Legal Bible.",
      "misconception": "Believing these are the same as the Wiring Regs (BS 7671); EAWR is the law, BS 7671 is the guidance."
    },
    {
      "term": "BS 7671",
      "simpleDefinition": "The UK national standard for electrical installations, also known as the IET Wiring Regulations.",
      "anchor": "The Wiring Regs.",
      "misconception": "Commonly mistaken for a statutory law, though it is technically a non-statutory guidance document."
    },
    {
      "term": "On-Site Guide",
      "simpleDefinition": "A non-statutory handbook that provides a simplified version of BS 7671 for small-scale electrical work.",
      "anchor": "The Pocket Guide.",
      "misconception": "Thinking this book replaces the full BS 7671 for complex industrial or commercial designs."
    },
    {
      "term": "Codes of Practice",
      "simpleDefinition": "Non-statutory documents that provide practical instructions on how to comply with health and safety law.",
      "anchor": "The 'How-To' Manuals.",
      "misconception": "Assuming these have no legal weight; they are often used in court to prove whether a person worked safely."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Statutory means it is the law.",
    "Non-statutory is the guidance we use to meet the law.",
    "BS 7671 is non-statutory guidance.",
    "EAWR is a statutory requirement.",
    "HASAWA is the primary health and safety law."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "BS 7671 is a statutory law.",
    "Non-statutory guidance is optional.",
    "Statutory regulations only apply to large companies.",
    "The On-Site Guide is a legal Act of Parliament."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "Statutory Regulations",
      "objective": "Identify specific statutory regulations that are legally binding in the electrical industry.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "In the UK electrical industry, statutory regulations are the 'Law of the Land.' These are Acts of Parliament or secondary legislation that you must follow by law. If you fail to comply with these, you are committing a criminal offense, which can lead to prosecution, heavy fines, or even imprisonment.",
        "The primary piece of legislation is the Health and Safety at Work Act (HASAWA). Think of this as the 'Umbrella Act' that covers all workplace safety. Underneath this, we have specific regulations that apply to our trade. The most critical for us is the Electricity at Work Regulations (EAWR), which is effectively the electrician's legal bible. It sets out mandatory safety requirements for electrical systems.",
        "Other statutory regulations you must recognize include the Electricity Safety, Quality and Continuity Regulations (ESQCR), which focus on the supply of electricity, and the Provision and Use of Work Equipment Regulations (PUWER). You also need to be aware of the Management of Health and Safety at Work Regulations, COSHH (hazardous substances), CDM (construction design), and specific rules for PPE, Manual Handling, and Noise at Work. Even the Environmental Act and the Disability Discrimination Act (DDA) fall into this statutory category."
      ],
      "hint": "Focus on the fact that statutory regulations are mandatory laws passed by Parliament, such as HASAWA and EAWR."
    },
    {
      "title": "Non-statutory Regulations and Guidance",
      "objective": "Identify non-statutory regulations and guidance documents used for best practice.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Non-statutory regulations are not laws themselves, but they are the industry's 'Rulebook.' They provide the technical detail and practical instructions on how to work safely and meet the broad requirements set by the law. While you won't be arrested specifically for 'breaking' a non-statutory rule, these documents are often used in court to prove whether or not you acted competently.",
        "The most famous non-statutory document is BS 7671, also known as the IET Wiring Regulations. A common misconception is that BS 7671 is a law; it is actually a national standard providing guidance. To help apply these rules on-site, we use the On-Site Guide, which is a simplified pocket version for smaller installations. Other non-statutory sources include IET Guidance Notes, various Codes of Practice, and the Unite Union Book.",
        "Think of the relationship like this: the statutory EAWR tells you that an installation must be safe, but the non-statutory BS 7671 tells you exactly how many clips to use or what size cable is required to make it safe. Following non-statutory guidance is the best way to ensure you are meeting your statutory legal duties."
      ],
      "hint": "Remember that BS 7671 and the On-Site Guide are guidance documents, not laws, making them non-statutory."
    }
  ]
}

